nodes.name: Ontology
nodes.description: A formal representation of knowledge as a set of concepts within a domain, and the relationships between those concepts.

nodes.name: Taxonomy
nodes.description: A hierarchical classification system that organizes concepts into groups and subgroups based on their characteristics and relationships.

nodes.name: Graph Theory
nodes.description: The study of graphs, which are mathematical structures used to represent pairwise relationships between objects.

nodes.name: Semantic Network
nodes.description: A network representation of concepts and their relationships, where nodes represent concepts and edges represent relationships.

nodes.name: Knowledge Representation
nodes.description: The process of representing knowledge in a way that can be understood and processed by a computer.

nodes.name: Upper Ontology
nodes.description: An upper ontology is an ontology that provides a foundational vocabulary and set of rules for other ontologies.

nodes.name: Domain Ontology
nodes.description: A domain ontology is an ontology that represents concepts specific to a particular domain or subject area.

nodes.name: Ontology Engineering
nodes.description: Ontology engineering is the process of creating, updating, and maintaining ontologies.

nodes.name: Ontology Mapping
nodes.description: Ontology mapping is the process of establishing correspondences between concepts and relationships in different ontologies.

nodes.name: Ontology Alignment
nodes.description: Ontology alignment is the process of aligning and integrating multiple ontologies to enable interoperability and semantic integration.

nodes.name: Cognitive Domain
nodes.description: The domain of learning that involves the development of intellectual skills, knowledge, and understanding.

nodes.name: Affective Domain
nodes.description: The domain of learning that involves the development of attitudes, values, and emotions.

nodes.name: Psychomotor Domain
nodes.description: The domain of learning that involves the development of physical and motor skills.

nodes.name: Vertex
nodes.description: A point or node in a graph

nodes.name: Edge
nodes.description: A connection between two vertices in a graph

nodes.name: Degree
nodes.description: The number of edges incident to a vertex

nodes.name: Path
nodes.description: A sequence of vertices in which each adjacent pair is connected by an edge

nodes.name: Cycle
nodes.description: A path that starts and ends at the same vertex

nodes.name: Node
nodes.description: A fundamental unit in a semantic network, representing a concept or entity

nodes.name: Link
nodes.description: A relationship between two nodes in a semantic network

nodes.name: Hierarchy
nodes.description: A structure in which nodes are organized in a parent-child relationship

nodes.name: Attribute
nodes.description: A characteristic or property of a node in a semantic network

nodes.name: Connection
nodes.description: An association between two nodes or concepts in a semantic network

nodes.name: Logical Representation
nodes.description: Representing knowledge using formal logic and reasoning

nodes.name: Ontology
nodes.description: Defining a common vocabulary of concepts and their relationships

nodes.name: Semantic Networks
nodes.description: Representing knowledge using a graph structure

nodes.name: Frame-based Representation
nodes.description: Structuring knowledge using objects and their attributes

nodes.name: Production Rules
nodes.description: Representing knowledge using a set of condition-action rules

nodes.name: Mathematics
nodes.description: The study of numbers, quantities, and shapes, as well as the relationships between them.

nodes.name: Physics
nodes.description: The study of matter, energy, and the interactions between them.

nodes.name: Chemistry
nodes.description: The study of the composition, properties, and behavior of substances.

nodes.name: Biology
nodes.description: The study of living organisms, including their structure, function, evolution, and interactions with the environment.

nodes.name: Computer Science
nodes.description: The study of computational systems and their applications.

nodes.name: Class
nodes.description: A group or category of objects or entities that have common characteristics

nodes.name: Property
nodes.description: An attribute or characteristic of a class

nodes.name: Relation
nodes.description: A connection or association between two or more entities

nodes.name: Instance
nodes.description: A particular occurrence or individual belonging to a class

nodes.name: Ontology
nodes.description: A formal representation of a set of concepts within a domain and the relationships between those concepts

nodes.name: Formal ontology
nodes.description: The study of ontology using formal methods and logic.

nodes.name: Ontology languages
nodes.description: The languages used for representing and expressing ontologies.

nodes.name: Ontology integration
nodes.description: The process of combining multiple ontologies into a single unified ontology.

nodes.name: Ontology evaluation
nodes.description: The assessment and measurement of the quality and effectiveness of ontologies.

nodes.name: Ontology alignment
nodes.description: The process of matching and aligning concepts and relationships between different ontologies.

nodes.name: Disambiguation
nodes.description: The process of resolving multiple possible meanings or interpretations of a concept or term in ontology mapping.

nodes.name: Alignment
nodes.description: The process of establishing correspondences and mappings between concepts in different ontologies.

nodes.name: Matching
nodes.description: The process of finding similar or equivalent concepts in different ontologies based on their structure, semantics, or other criteria.

nodes.name: Integration
nodes.description: The process of combining multiple ontologies into a single unified ontology by resolving conflicts and overlapping concepts.

nodes.name: Evaluation
nodes.description: The process of assessing the quality, accuracy, and effectiveness of ontology mapping techniques and tools.

nodes.name: Semantic Similarity
nodes.description: Measures the similarity between two entities based on the meaning of their attributes and relationships

nodes.name: Instance Matching
nodes.description: Identifies corresponding instances or individuals in different ontologies

nodes.name: Schema Matching
nodes.description: Matches the structure and elements of the ontologies to identify correspondences between the classes, properties, and relationships

nodes.name: Mapping Creation
nodes.description: Creates mappings or correspondences between the entities of two ontologies

nodes.name: Conflict Detection and Resolution
nodes.description: Identifies and resolves conflicts or inconsistencies in the mappings between ontologies

nodes.name: Knowledge
nodes.description: The ability to recall or recognize facts, information, or concepts.

nodes.name: Comprehension
nodes.description: The ability to understand the meaning of information and to explain it in one's own words.

nodes.name: Application
nodes.description: The ability to use information or concepts in new situations or solve problems using previously acquired knowledge or skills.

nodes.name: Analysis
nodes.description: The ability to break down complex information into its constituent parts and understand the relationships between these parts.

nodes.name: Synthesis
nodes.description: The ability to combine parts or elements to form a new whole or create new patterns or relationships.

nodes.name: Evaluation
nodes.description: The ability to judge the value or quality of information, ideas, or methods based on a set of criteria.

nodes.name: Attitude
nodes.description: The emotional response or evaluation of a person towards a particular object, person, or situation.

nodes.name: Emotion
nodes.description: A complex pattern of physiological, psychological, and cognitive reactions, triggered by a specific event or stimulus.

nodes.name: Values
nodes.description: Beliefs or principles that guide behavior and decision-making.

nodes.name: Empathy
nodes.description: The ability to understand and share the thoughts, feelings, and experiences of others.

nodes.name: Self-awareness
nodes.description: The knowledge and understanding of one's own thoughts, feelings, and actions.

nodes.name: Perception
nodes.description: The ability to interpret and understand sensory information.

nodes.name: Gross motor skills
nodes.description: The ability to control and coordinate large muscle movements.

nodes.name: Fine motor skills
nodes.description: The ability to control and coordinate small muscle movements.

nodes.name: Physical fitness
nodes.description: The ability to engage in physical activity and maintain an overall state of health and well-being.

nodes.name: Balance and coordination
nodes.description: The ability to maintain body balance and perform tasks requiring precise movements.

nodes.name: Graph
nodes.description: A set of vertices and edges.

nodes.name: Directed graph
nodes.description: A graph where each edge is directed from one vertex to another.

nodes.name: Weighted graph
nodes.description: A graph where each edge is assigned a weight.

nodes.name: Connected graph
nodes.description: A graph where there is a path between every pair of vertices.

nodes.name: Undirected graph
nodes.description: A graph where the edges have no direction.

nodes.name: Edge Length
nodes.description: The distance between two vertices in a graph.

nodes.name: Edge Weight
nodes.description: A numerical value assigned to an edge in a graph to represent a cost or distance.

nodes.name: Edge Connectivity
nodes.description: The minimum number of edges that must be removed from a graph to disconnect it.

nodes.name: Edge Coloring
nodes.description: Assigning colors to the edges of a graph such that no two adjacent edges have the same color.

nodes.name: Bachelor's degree
nodes.description: An undergraduate academic degree awarded by colleges and universities upon completion of a specific course of study

nodes.name: Master's degree
nodes.description: A graduate academic degree awarded by colleges and universities upon completion of a specific course of study

nodes.name: Doctorate degree
nodes.description: The highest level of academic degree awarded by colleges and universities upon completion of a specific course of study and original research

nodes.name: Associate degree
nodes.description: An undergraduate academic degree typically awarded by community colleges upon completion of a specific course of study

nodes.name: Honours degree
nodes.description: An academic degree awarded to students with outstanding performance in their undergraduate studies

nodes.name: Path Planning
nodes.description: The process of determining an optimal path from a starting point to a goal point, considering obstacles and constraints.

nodes.name: Graph Theory
nodes.description: The study of mathematical structures used to model pairwise relations between objects, such as nodes and edges in a graph.

nodes.name: Optimization
nodes.description: The process of finding the best solution for a given problem, often involving maximizing or minimizing an objective function.

nodes.name: Motion Planning
nodes.description: The process of determining a sequence of valid motions for a robot to achieve a desired goal, considering constraints and dynamics.

nodes.name: Search Algorithms
nodes.description: Methods designed to find a solution or path from a starting state to a desired goal state in a search space.

nodes.name: Revolution
nodes.description: A Cycle where a fixed point rotates around an axis

nodes.name: Recurrence
nodes.description: A Cycle that repeats in a pattern

nodes.name: Periodicity
nodes.description: A Cycle with a regular interval between occurrences

nodes.name: Pendulum
nodes.description: A Cycle of oscillation between two extreme points

nodes.name: Seasonality
nodes.description: A Cycle that is influenced by the change of seasons

nodes.name: Event-driven programming
nodes.description: A programming paradigm in which the flow of the program is determined by events, such as user actions or sensor inputs.

nodes.name: Asynchronous programming
nodes.description: A programming model that allows for non-blocking execution and handling of multiple tasks concurrently.

nodes.name: Callback functions
nodes.description: Functions that are passed as arguments to other functions and are executed when a certain event occurs.

nodes.name: File system operations
nodes.description: Operations related to reading, writing, and managing files or directories on a computer system.

nodes.name: Networking
nodes.description: The practice of connecting nodes in a network to enable communication and data exchange.

nodes.name: Web page
nodes.description: A document on the World Wide Web.

nodes.name: Hyperlink
nodes.description: A reference to data that the reader can directly follow, either by clicking, tapping, or hovering.

nodes.name: Anchor text
nodes.description: The clickable text in a hyperlink.

nodes.name: URL
nodes.description: A specific type of Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), a string of characters that provides a reference to a web resource.

nodes.name: HTML
nodes.description: A markup language used to structure content on the web.
